<section xml:id="section-square-and-nth-root-properties">
  <title>Square and <m>n</m>th Root Properties</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-evaluate-nth-roots" text="local">MTH 65 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-recognize-even-root-of-negative-not-real" text="local">MTH 65 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-simplify-radical-expressions" text="local">MTH 65 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we learn what expressions like <m>\sqrt{25}</m> and <m>\sqrt[3]{27}</m> mean,
      and some of the properties they have that allow for simplification.
    </p>
    <!-- TODO: Videos use prime factorization instead of factor pairs -->
    <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-flbQmCojUofDfyHSDrpt72"/>
    </figure>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Square Roots</title>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
      <stack>
        <p>
          Consider the non-negative number <m>25</m>.
          You can ask the question <q>what number multiplies by itself to make <m>25</m>?</q>
          We use the symbol <m>\sqrt{25}</m> to represent the answer to this question,
          whether or not you know the <q>answer</q>.
        </p>
        <p>
          A geometric visualization of the same idea is to imagine a square with <m>25</m> units of area inside it.
          What would a side length have to be? We use <m>\sqrt{25}</m> to represent that side length.
        </p>
      </stack>
      <image>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(D.base)]
            \node[node distance=0cm, inner xsep=0cm] (A) at (0,0) {$(\phantom{5})$};
            \node[node distance=0cm, inner xsep=0cm, right=of A] (B) {$(\phantom{5})$}; 
            \node[node distance=0cm, inner xsep=0cm, right=of B] (C) {${}=25$}; 
            \node[above=1cm of $(A)!0.5!(B)$] (D) {$\sqrt{25}$};
            \draw[->] (D.south) -- (A.north);
            \draw[->] (D.south) -- (B.north);
          \end{tikzpicture}
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(A.base)]
            \draw[fill=firstcolor!30] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5,5) -- (0,5) -- cycle;
            \node[below] at (2.5,0) {$\sqrt{25}$};
            \node[left] at (0,2.5) {$\sqrt{25}$};
            \node (A) at (2.5,2.5) {25};
            \foreach \i in {1,2,3,4} {
              \draw[gray,very thin] (\i,0) -- (\i,5);
              \draw[gray,very thin] (0,\i) -- (5,\i);
            };
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </sidebyside>

    <definition xml:id="definition-square-root">
      <title>Square Root</title>
      <idx>square root</idx>

      <notation>
        <usage><m>\sqrt{x}</m></usage>
        <shortdescription>square root</shortdescription>
      </notation>

      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a non-negative number <m>x</m>,
          if <m>r\cdot r=x</m> for some positive number <m>r</m>,
          then <m>r</m> is called the <term>square root</term>
              <idx><h>square root</h></idx>
          of <m>x</m>, and we can write <m>\sqrt{x}</m> instead of <m>r</m>.
          The <m>\sqrt{\phantom{x}}</m> symbol is called the <term>radical</term>
              <idx><h>radical</h></idx>
          or the <term>root</term>.
              <idx><h>root</h></idx>
          We call expressions with the <m>\sqrt{\phantom{x}}</m> symbol
          <term>radical expressions</term>.
          The number inside the radical is called the <term>radicand</term>.
              <idx><h>radicand</h></idx>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      For example, if you are confronted with the expression <m>\sqrt{16}</m>,
      you should think about the equation <m>r\cdot r=16</m> (or if you prefer, <m>r^2=16</m>)
      and ask yourself if you know a positive value for <m>r</m> that solves that equation.
      Of course, <m>4</m> is a non-negative solution.
      So we an say <m>\sqrt{16}=4</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      To demonstrate more of the vocabulary, both <m>\sqrt{2}</m> and <m>3\sqrt{2}</m> are radical expressions.
      In both expressions, the number <m>2</m> is the radicand.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="69% 25%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        The word <q>radical</q> means something like <q>on the fringes</q>
        when used in politics, sports, and other places.
        It actually has that same meaning in math,
        when you consider a square with area <m>A</m> as in <xref ref="figure-radical">Figure</xref>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="figure-radical">
        <caption><q>Radical</q> means <q>off to the side.</q></caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>A drawing of a square labeled with area A; the side lengths are labeled the square root of A</shortdescription>

            <latex-image>
                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw [fill=firstcolor!30] (0,0) rectangle (2.5,2.5);
                    \node at (1.25,1.25) {area $A$};
                    \node[right] at (2.5,1.25) {$\sqrt{A}$};
                    \node[below] at (1.25,0) {side length $\sqrt{A}$};
                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
        </image>

      </figure>
    </sidebyside>

    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="bottom">
