  <subsection>
    <title>Square Root Decimal Values</title>
    <p>
      Most square roots have decimal places that go on forever.
      Take <m>\sqrt{5}</m> as an example. The number <m>5</m> is between two perfect squares,
      <m>4</m> and <m>9</m>. Therefore, as demonstrated in <xref ref="figure-compare-square-roots">Figure</xref>,
      <m>\sqrt{4}\lt\sqrt{5}\lt\sqrt{9}</m>. In other words,
      <me>
        2\lt\sqrt{5}\lt3
      </me>
      So <m>\sqrt{5}</m> has a decimal value somewhere between <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="figure-compare-square-roots">
      <caption><m>2\lt\sqrt{5}\lt3</m></caption>
      <image>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[] (0,0) --++ (3,0) --++ (0,3) --++ (-3,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[fill=firstcolor!30] (0,0) --++ (2,0) --++ (0,2) --++ (-2,0) -- cycle;
            \foreach \i in {1,2} {
              \draw[gray,very thin] (\i,0) -- (\i,3);
              \draw[gray,very thin] (0,\i) -- (3,\i);
            };
            \draw (0,0) --++ (2,0) --++ (0,2) --++ (-2,0) -- cycle;
            \node at (1,1) {4};
            \node (A) at (0,0) {};
            \node (B) at (2,0) {};
            \node (C) at (1,-1) {$\sqrt{4}$};
            \draw (A.south) -- (C.west);
            \draw (B.south) -- (C.east);
          \end{tikzpicture}
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[] (0,0) --++ (3,0) --++ (0,3) --++ (-3,0) -- cycle;
            \draw[fill=secondcolor!30] (0,0) --++ (2.236,0) --++ (0,2.236) --++ (-2.236,0) -- cycle;
            \foreach \i in {1,2} {
              \draw[gray,very thin] (\i,0) -- (\i,3);
              \draw[gray,very thin] (0,\i) -- (3,\i);
            };
            \draw (0,0) --++ (2.236,0) --++ (0,2.236) --++ (-2.236,0) -- cycle;
            \node at (1.118,1.118) {5};
            \node (A) at (0,0) {};
            \node (B) at (2.236,0) {};
            \node (C) at (1.118,-1) {$\sqrt{5}$};
            \draw (A.south) -- (C.west);
            \draw (B.south) -- (C.east);
          \end{tikzpicture}
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[fill=thirdcolor!30] (0,0) --++ (3,0) --++ (0,3) --++ (-3,0) -- cycle;
            \foreach \i in {1,2} {
              \draw[gray,very thin] (\i,0) -- (\i,3);
              \draw[gray,very thin] (0,\i) -- (3,\i);
            };
            \node at (1.5,1.5) {9};
            \node (A) at (0,0) {};
            \node (B) at (3,0) {};
            \node (C) at (1.5,-1) {$\sqrt{9}$};
            \draw (A.south) -- (C.west);
            \draw (B.south) -- (C.east);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      With a calculator, we can see:
      <me>
        \sqrt{5}\approx2.236
      </me>
      Actually the decimal will not terminate,
      and that is why we used the <m>\approx</m> symbol instead of an equals sign.
      To get <m>2.236</m> we rounded down slightly from the true value of <m>\sqrt{5}</m>.
      With a calculator, we can check that
      <m>2.236^2=4.999696</m>, a little shy of <m>5</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      When the radicand is a perfect square,
      its square root is a rational number.
      If the radicand is not a perfect square, the square root is irrational.
      (It has a decimal that goes on forever without any pattern that is easy to see.)
      We want to be able to estimate square roots without using a calculator.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        To estimate <m>\sqrt{10}</m> without a calculator,
        we can find the nearest perfect squares that are whole numbers on either side of <m>10</m>.
        Recall that the perfect squares are
        <m>1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64,\dots</m> The perfect square that is just below <m>10</m> is <m>9</m> and the perfect square just above <m>10</m> is <m>16</m>.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="47%">
        <image>
          <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[numberline,
                            xtick={9,10,16},
                            minor xtick={0,...,20},
                            xmin=0,
                            xmax=20,
                            ]
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(9,0)};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(10,0)};
                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(16,0)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            ]]>
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        This tells us that <m>\sqrt{10}</m> is between
        <m>\sqrt{9}</m> and <m>\sqrt{16}</m>,
        or between <m>3</m> and <m>4</m>.
        We can also say that <m>\sqrt{10}</m> is much closer to <m>3</m> than <m>4</m> because <m>10</m> is closer to <m>9</m>,
        so we think <m>3.1</m> or <m>3.2</m> would be a good estimate.
      </p>

      <p>
        To check our estimates (<m>3.1</m> or <m>3.2</m>) we can square them and see if the result is close to <m>10</m>.
        We find <m>3.1^2=9.61</m> and <m>3.2^2=10.24</m>, so our estimates are pretty good.
      </p>
    </example>

