    <exercise>
      <webwork>
            <pg-code>
                Context("LimitedNumeric");
                Context()->flags->set(tolType=>'absolute',tolerance=>'0.15');
            </pg-code>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Estimate <m>\sqrt{19}</m> without a calculator.
            </p>

            <p>
              <var name="'4.35'" width="5" />
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              The radicand, <m>19</m>, is between <m>16</m> and <m>25</m>,
              so <m>\sqrt{19}</m> is between
              <m>\sqrt{16}</m> and <m>\sqrt{25}</m>,
              or between <m>4</m> and <m>5</m>.
              We notice that <m>19</m> is in the middle between <m>16</m> and <m>25</m> but closer to <m>16</m>.
              We estimate <m>\sqrt{19}</m> to be about <m>4.4</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
              We can check our estimate by calculating:
              <me>
                4.4^2=19.36
              </me>
              So <m>4.4^2</m> is close to <m>19</m>, and <m>4.4</m> is close to <m>\sqrt{19}</m>.
            </p>
          </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsection-cube-root-and-higher-order-roots">
    <title>Cube Root and Higher Order Roots</title>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
      <stack>
        <p>
          The concept behind a square root easily extends to a <term>cube root</term>.
          What if we have a number in mind, like <m>64</m>,
          and we would like to know what number can be multiplied with itself <em>three</em> times to make <m>64</m>?
        </p>
        <p>
          A geometric visualization of the same idea is to imagine a cube with <m>64</m> units of area inside it.
          What would an edge length have to be? We use <m>\sqrt[3]{64}</m> to represent that edge length.
        </p>
      </stack>
      <image>
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(E.base)]
            \node[node distance=0cm, inner xsep=0cm] (A) at (0,0) {$(\phantom{4})$};
            \node[node distance=0cm, inner xsep=0cm, right=of A] (B) {$(\phantom{4})$}; 
            \node[node distance=0cm, inner xsep=0cm, right=of B] (C) {$(\phantom{4})$}; 
            \node[node distance=0cm, inner xsep=0cm, right=of C] (D) {${}=64$}; 
            \node[above=1cm of $(A)!0.5!(C)$] (E) {$\sqrt[3]{64}$};
            \draw[->] (E.south) -- (A.north);
            \draw[->] (E.south) -- (B.north);
            \draw[->] (E.south) -- (C.north);
          \end{tikzpicture}
          \begin{tikzpicture}[baseline=(A.base)]
            \coordinate (v) at (14,12);
            \foreach \i in {0,...,4}{
            \draw (\i,0) -- (\i,4) -- ( $ (\i,4)!.142!(v) $ );
            }
            \foreach \j in {0,...,4}{
            \draw (0,\j) -- (4,\j) -- ( $ (4,\j)!.142!(v) $ );
            }
            \foreach \k in {0.04,0.076,0.110,0.142}{
            \draw ( $ (4,0)!{\k}!(v) $) -- ( $ (4,4)!{\k}!(v) $) -- ( $ (0,4)!{\k}!(v) $);
            }
            \coordinate (A) at (0,2);
            \node[below] at (2,0) {$\sqrt[3]{64}$};
            \node[left] at (0,2) {$\sqrt[3]{64}$};
            \path (4,0) -- ( $ (4,0)!.142!(v) $ ) node[sloped,below,pos=0.5] {$\sqrt[3]{64}$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </sidebyside>

    <definition xml:id="definition-nth-root">
      <title><m>n</m>th Root</title>
      <idx>nth root</idx>

      <notation>
        <usage><m>\sqrt[n]{x}</m></usage>
        <shortdescription>nth root</shortdescription>
      </notation>

      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a number <m>x</m>,
          if <m>\overbrace{r\cdot r\cdot \cdots \cdot r}^{n\text{ times}}=x</m> for some number <m>r</m>,
          then <m>r</m> is called an <term><m>n</m>th root</term>
              <idx><h sortby="nth root"><m>n</m>th root</h></idx>
          of <m>x</m>. (Or if you prefer, when <m>r^n=x</m>.)
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                When <m>n</m> is odd, there is always exactly one real number <m>n</m>th root for any <m>x</m>,
                and we write <m>\sqrt[n]{x}</m> to mean that one <m>n</m>th root.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                When <m>n</m> is even and <m>x</m> is positive, there are two real number <m>n</m>th roots,
                one of which is positive and the other of which is negative.
                We write <m>\sqrt[n]{x}</m> to mean the positive <m>n</m>th root.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                When <m>n</m> is even and <m>x</m> is negative, there aren't any real number <m>n</m>th roots,
                and we say that <m>\sqrt[n]{x}</m> is <q>not a real number</q>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
          The <m>\sqrt[n]{\phantom{x}}</m> symbol is called the <term><m>n</m>th radical</term>
              <idx><h sortby="nth radical"><m>n</m>th radical</h></idx>
          or the <term><m>n</m>th root</term>.
              <idx><h sortby="nth root"><m>n</m>th root</h></idx>
          We call expressions with the <m>\sqrt[n]{\phantom{x}}</m> symbol
          <term>radical expressions</term>.
          The number inside the radical is called the <term>radicand</term>.
              <idx><h>radicand</h></idx>
          The <term>index</term>
              <idx><h>index</h></idx>
          of a radical is the number <m>n</m>
          in <m>\sqrt[n]{\phantom{x}}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      As noted earlier, when we have <m>\sqrt[3]{\phantom{x}}</m>,
      we can say <q>cube root</q> instead of <q><m>3</m>rd root</q>.
      Also, when we have <m>\sqrt[2]{\phantom{x}}</m>,
      we can say <q>square root</q> instead of <q><m>2</m>nd root</q> and we can simply write <m>\sqrt{x}</m> instead.
    </p>

    <p>
      For some examples of <m>n</m>th roots:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[3]{8}=2</m>, because <m>\overbrace{2\cdot2\cdot2}^{\text{3 instances}}=8</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[4]{81}=3</m>, because <m>\overbrace{3\cdot3\cdot3\cdot3}^{\text{4 instances}}=81</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[5]{-32}=-2</m>, because <m>\overbrace{(-2)\cdot(-2)\cdot(-2)\cdot(-2)\cdot(-2)}^{\text{5 instances}}=-32</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <p>
      As with square roots, in general an <m>n</m>th root's decimal value is a decimal that goes on forever.
      For example, <m>\sqrt[3]{20}\approx2.714\ldots</m>.
      For practical applications, we may want to use a calculator to find a decimal approximation
      to an <m>n</m>th root.
      Some calculators will do this for you directly, and some will not.
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Maybe your calculator has a button that looks like <m>\sqrt[x]{y}</m>.
            Then you should be able to type something like <c>3 </c><m>\sqrt[x]{y}</m><c> 20</c>
            to get <m>\sqrt[3]{20}\approx2.714\ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Maybe your calculator has a button that looks like <m>\sqrt[n]{\phantom{y}}</m>.
            Then you should be able to type something like <c>3 </c><m>\sqrt[n]{\phantom{y}}</m><c> 20</c>
            to get <m>\sqrt[3]{20}\approx2.714\ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Maybe your calculator allows you to type letters, parentheses, and commas,
            and you can type <c>root(3,20)</c> to get <m>\sqrt[3]{20}\approx2.714\ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Maybe your calculator allows you to type letters, parentheses, and commas,
            but the syntax for an <m>n</m>th root is reversed from the last example,
            and you can type <c>root(20,3)</c> to get <m>\sqrt[3]{20}\approx2.714\ldots</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If your calculator has none of the above options,
            then you should be able to type <c>20^(1/3)</c> as a way to get <m>\sqrt[3]{20}\approx2.714\ldots</m>.
            This is technically using mathematics we will learn in <xref ref="section-radical-expressions-and-rational-exponents">Section</xref>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      Try using your own calculator to calculate <m>\sqrt[3]{20}</m>
      so that you can become familiar with whatever method it uses.
    </p>

    <example>
      <sidebyside widths="70% 24%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          A pyramid has a square base, and its height is equal to one side length of the square at its base.
          In this situation, the volume <m>V</m> of the pyramid,
          in <quantity><unit base="inch" exp="3"/></quantity>,
          is given by <m>V=\frac{1}{3}s^3</m>,
          where <m>s</m> is the pyramid's base side length in <quantity><unit base="inch"/></quantity>.
          Archimedes dropped the pyramid in a bathtub, and judging by how high the water level rose,
          the volume of the pyramid is <quantity><mag>243</mag><unit base="inch" exp="3"/></quantity>
          (a little more than <quantity><mag>1</mag><unit base="gallon"/></quantity>).
          How tall is the pyramid?
        </p>
        <image>
          <latex-image>
            \tdplotsetmaincoords{70}{-20}
            \begin{tikzpicture}[tdplot_main_coords,line cap=butt,line join=bevel]
              \pgfmathsetmacro{\B}{2}
              \pgfmathsetmacro{\H}{2}
              \draw[firstcolor,thick] (-\B/2,-\B/2,0) -- (\B/2,-\B/2,0) -- (\B/2,\B/2,0) -- (-\B/2,\B/2,0) -- cycle;
              \node[below left] at (-\B/2,0,0) {$s$};
              \node[below] at (0,-\B/2,0) {$s$};
              \draw[firstcolor,thick] (\B/2,\B/2,0) -- (0,0,\H);
              \draw[dashed,firstcolor] (0,0,0) -- (0,0,\H) coordinate[midway](aux1);
              \draw[firstcolor] (0,0,0.3) -- (0.3,0,0.3) -- (0.3,0,0);
              \coordinate (aux3) at (1,0,0);
              \draw[firstcolor,thick,fill=secondcolor,fill opacity=0.3] (-\B/2,-\B/2,0) -- (0,0,\H) -- (\B/2,-\B/2,0) -- cycle;
              \draw[firstcolor,thick,fill=firstcolor,fill opacity=0.3] (-\B/2,-\B/2,0) -- (0,0,\H) -- (-\B/2,\B/2,0) -- cycle;
              \begin{scope}[tdplot_screen_coords]
                \draw (aux1) -- ++ (1,0.1) node[right,font=\itshape] {$s$};
              \end{scope}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        The equation tells us that:
        <me>
          243=\frac{1}{3}s^3
        </me>
        We can multiply on both sides by <m>3</m> and:
        <me>
          729=s^3
        </me>
        This means that <m>s</m> is <m>\sqrt[3]{729}</m>. A calculator tells us that this is <m>9</m>.
        So the pyramid's height is <m>9</m> inches.
      </p>
    </example>

