  <subsection>
    <title>Roots of Negative Numbers</title>
    <p>
      Can we find the square root of a negative number,
      such as <m>\sqrt{-64}</m>?
      How about its cube root, <m>\sqrt[3]{-64}</m>?
    </p>

    <p>
      As noted in <xref ref="definition-nth-root">Defintion</xref>, when the index of an <m>n</m>th root is odd,
      there will always be a real number <m>n</m>th root even when the radicand is negative.
      For example, <m>\sqrt[3]{-64}</m> is <m>-4</m>, because <m>(-4)(-4)(-4)=-64</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      When the index of an <m>n</m>th root is even, it is a problem to have a negative radicand.
      For example, to find <m>\sqrt{-64}</m>,
      you would need to find a value <m>r</m> so that <m>r\cdot r=-64</m>.
      But whether <m>r</m> is positive or negative, multiplying it by itself will give a positive result.
      It could never be <m>-64</m>. So there is no way to have a real number square root of a negative number.
      And the same thing is true for <em>any</em> even index <m>n</m>th root with a negative radicand,
      such as <m>\sqrt[4]{-64}</m>.
      An even-indexed root of a negative number is not a real number.
    </p>

    <aside>
      <title>Imaginary Numbers</title>
      <p>
        Mathematicians imagined a new type of number,
        neither positive nor negative,
        that would multiply by itself to make a negative result.
        But that is beyond the scope of this section.
      </p>
    </aside>

    <p>
      If you are confronted with an expression like <m>\sqrt{-25}</m> or <m>\sqrt[4]{-16}</m>
      (any square root or even-indexed root of a negative number),
      you can state that the expression <q>is not real</q>
      or that it is <q>not defined</q> (as a real number). Don't get carried away though.
      Expressions like <m>\sqrt[3]{-27}</m> and <m>\sqrt[5]{-1}</m> <em>are</em> defined,
      because the index is odd.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Radical Rules and Exponent Rules</title>

    <p>
      In an earlier chapter, we learned some algebra rules for exponents.
      A summary of these rules is in <xref ref="list-exponent-rules">List</xref>.
      There are a couple of very similar rules for radicals, presented here without motivation.
      (These rules are easier to explain once we study <xref ref="section-radical-expressions-and-rational-exponents">Section</xref>.)
    </p>

    <list xml:id="list-radical-rules">
      <title>Rules of Radicals for Multiplication and Division</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          If <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are positive real numbers,
          and <m>m</m> is a positive <xref ref="item-integer-definition" text="custom">integer</xref>,
          then we have the following rules:
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <dl>
        <li xml:id="item-radical-rules-product">
          <title>Root of a Product Rule</title>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[m]{a\cdot b} = \sqrt[m]{a} \cdot \sqrt[m]{b}</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li xml:id="item-radical-rules-quotient">
          <title>Root of a Quotient Rule</title>
          <p>
            <m>\sqrt[m]{\frac{a}{b}} = \frac{\sqrt[m]{a}}{\sqrt[m]{b}}</m>
            as long as <m>b \neq 0</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </list>

    <p>
      Knowing these algebra rules helps to make complicated radical expressions look simpler.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Simplify <m>\sqrt{18}</m>. Anything we can do to make the radicand a smaller simpler number is helpful.
        Note that <m>18=9\cdot2</m>, so we can write
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt{18}\amp=\sqrt{9\cdot 2}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{2}\amp\amp\text{according to the }<xref ref="item-radical-rules-product" text="title"/></mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=3\sqrt{2}</mrow>
        </md>
        This expression <m>3\sqrt{2}</m> is considered <q>simpler</q> than <m>\sqrt{18}</m> because the radicand is so much smaller.
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>contextForm.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
          <pg-code>
            Context("Form");
            $a = Formula('6sqrt(2)');
          </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Simplify <m>\sqrt{72}</m>.
          </p>
          <instruction>
            If you need to enter a square root, like <m>\sqrt{2}</m>, type <c>sqrt(2)</c>.
          </instruction>
          <p>
            <var name="$a" width="15"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            As with the previous example, it will help if <m>72</m> can be written as a product of a perfect square.
            In this case, <m>4</m> divides <m>72</m>, and <m>72=4\cdot18</m>. So
            <md>
              <mrow>\sqrt{72}\amp=\sqrt{4\cdot18}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{18}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=2\sqrt{18}</mrow>
            </md>
            But we aren't done. Can <m>18</m> can be written as a product of a perfect square?
            Yes, because <m>18=9\cdot2</m>. So
            <md>
              <mrow>\sqrt{72}\amp=2\sqrt{18}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=2\sqrt{9\cdot2}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=2\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=2\cdot3\sqrt{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=6\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            </md>
            This is as simple as we can make this expression.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <example>
      <p>
        Simplify <m>\sqrt[3]{80}</m>. Anything we can do to make the radicand a smaller simpler number is helpful.
        With lessons learned from the previous examples,
        maybe there is a way to rewrite <m>80</m> as the product of two numbers in a helpful way.
        Since we have a <em>cube</em> root,
        writing <m>80</m> as a product of a perfect <em>cube</em> would be helpful.
        We can write <m>80=8\cdot10</m>, where <m>8</m> is a perfect cube.
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt[3]{80}\amp=\sqrt[3]{8\cdot 10}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[3]{8}\cdot\sqrt[3]{10}\amp\amp\text{according to the }<xref ref="item-radical-rules-product" text="title"/></mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=2\sqrt[3]{10}</mrow>
        </md>
        This expression <m>2\sqrt[3]{10}</m> is considered <q>simpler</q> than <m>\sqrt[3]{80}</m> because the radicand is so much smaller.
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>contextForm.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
          <pg-code>
            Context("Form");
            $a = Formula('2root(4,3)');
          </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Simplify <m>\sqrt[4]{48}</m>.
          </p>
          <instruction>
            If you need to enter a <m>4</m>th root, like <m>\sqrt[4]{2}</m>, type <c>root(4,2)</c>.
          </instruction>
          <p>
            <var name="$a" width="15"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            As with the previous example, it will help if <m>48</m> can be written as a product of a <m>4</m>th power.
            In this case, <m>16</m> divides <m>48</m>, and <m>48=16\cdot3</m>. So
            <md>
              <mrow>\sqrt[4]{48}\amp=\sqrt[4]{16\cdot3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[4]{16}\sqrt[4]{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp=2\sqrt[4]{3}</mrow>
            </md>
            This is as simple as we can make this expression.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      When a radical is applied to a fraction, the <xref ref="item-radical-rules-quotient" text="title"/> is useful.
    </p>

    <example>
      <p>
        Simplify <m>\sqrt{\frac{8}{25}}</m>. According to the <xref ref="item-radical-rules-quotient" text="title"/>,
        <md>
          <mrow>\sqrt{\frac{8}{25}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt{8}}{\sqrt{25}}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{8}}{5}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{4\cdot2}}{5}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{2}}{5}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp=\frac{2\sqrt{2}}{5}</mrow>
        </md>
        This is as simple as we can make this expression, unless you prefer to write it as <m>\frac{2}{5}\sqrt{2}</m>.
      </p>
    </example>


    <exercise>
      <webwork>
        <pg-macros>
          <macro-file>contextForm.pl</macro-file>
        </pg-macros>
          <pg-code>
            Context("Form");
            $a[0] = Formula('1/6');
            $a[1] = Formula('2/3');
            $a[2] = OneOf(Formula('3root(3,3)/5'), Formula('3/5 root(3,3)'));
          </pg-code>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Simplify each of the following.
            <ol marker="a." cols="3">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\sqrt{\dfrac{1}{36}}=</m><var name="$a[0]" width="25" />
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\sqrt[3]{\dfrac{8}{27}}=</m><var name="$a[1]" width="25" />
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\sqrt[3]{\dfrac{81}{125}}=</m><var name="$a[2]" width="25" />
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a." cols="3">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>
                    \begin{aligned}[t]
                      \sqrt{\frac{1}{36}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt{1}}{\sqrt{36}}\\
                      \amp=\frac{1}{6}
                    \end{aligned}
                  </m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>
                    \begin{aligned}[t]
                      \sqrt[3]{\frac{8}{27}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt[3]{8}}{\sqrt[3]{27}}\\
                      \amp=\frac{2}{3}
                    \end{aligned}
                  </m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>
                    \begin{aligned}[t]
                      \sqrt[3]{\frac{81}{125}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt[3]{81}}{\sqrt[3]{125}}\\
                      \amp=\frac{\sqrt[3]{81}}{5}\\
                      \amp=\frac{\sqrt[3]{27\cdot3}}{5}\\
                      \amp=\frac{\sqrt[3]{27}\sqrt[3]{3}}{5}\\
                      \amp=\frac{3\sqrt[3]{3}}{5}\\
                    \end{aligned}
                  </m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </webwork>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>


  <subsection>
    <title>Multiplying Square Root Expressions</title>
    <p>
      We can use the <xref ref="item-radical-rules-product" text="title" />
      and the <xref ref="item-radical-rules-quotient" text="title" /> to multiply and divide square root expressions.
      We want to simplify each radical first to keep the radicands as small as possible.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Multiply <m>\sqrt{8}\cdot\sqrt{54}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We will simplify each radical first,
          and then multiply them together.
          We do not want to multiply
          <m>8\cdot54</m> because we will end up with a larger number that is harder to factor.
          <md>
            <mrow>\sqrt{8}\cdot\sqrt{54}\amp=\sqrt{4\cdot2}\cdot\sqrt{9\cdot6}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{9}\cdot\sqrt{6}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=2\sqrt{2}\cdot3\sqrt{6}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=6\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{6}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=6\sqrt{12}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=6\sqrt{4\cdot3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=6\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=6\cdot2\sqrt{3}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=12\sqrt{3}</mrow>
          </md>
          It is worth noting that this is considered as simple as we canmake it, because the radicand of <m>3</m> is so small.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
